pr_review_comment_body:
Very much needed feature IMHO. I merged it in my own fork, and I'm using it now.
I believe for correctness, the next line should also be changed IIUC, from:

    return source, None, lambda: source == self.mapping.get(template)

to:

    return source, None, lambda: options == self.mapping.get(template)

because `source` and `self.mapping.get(template)` will otherwise never be equal.

@jerome-poisson I see your point. I think the issue might be on the client then.

Afaik, when a schedule saved by user, client sends date, time and timezone to server. Server uses PUBLISH_SCHEDULE field for the raw datetime value (as given by client) and uses SCHEDULE_SETTINGS to keep the UTC values.

You can test this by saving a story with schedule (without publishing) and if you re-open the story to see how the client sets date, time and timezone values; if the problem in the client you might see the same problem there as well.

If localMode, the modelPoolSize always equals to 1 when engineType == MKlBlas by defaults.

    private def initThreadPool(core : Int) : Unit = {
      val defaultPoolSize: Int = System.getProperty("bigdl.utils.Engine.defaultPoolSize",
        (core * 50).toString).toInt
      if(_default == null || _default.getPoolSize != defaultPoolSize) {
        _default = new ThreadPool(defaultPoolSize)
      }
  
      val modelPoolSize: Int = if (engineType == MklBlas) {
        1
      } else {
        core
      }
  
      if(_model == null || _model.getPoolSize != modelPoolSize) {
        _model = new ThreadPool(modelPoolSize)
        _model.setMKLThread(MKL.getMklNumThreads)
      }
    }

I think you can safely drop the `forEach` and use `update` instead (faster for this, one query instead of one + `nbusers`):
```javascript
const result = db.user.find(
    {active: true, confirmed_at: null},
    {$set: {'confirmed_at': new Date()}},
    {multi: true}
);
print(`${result.nModified} users migrated.');
```

@haikuginger Thanks for documenting this control flow extensively :)

One suggestion regarding readability: It would be least surprising if the code were checking values of `received_expiration_time` and `max_session_length` in the same order every time. That is:

```python
        if received_expiration_time is None and max_session_length is None:
            # ...
        elif received_expiration_time is None and max_session_length is not None:
            # ...
        elif received_expiration_time is not None and max_session_length is None:
            # ...
        else:
            # ...
```

@sxjscience 
It still does not work even though kernel is set accordingly. By the way, I do not think the original implementation does wrong here, as it also considers the global_pool and resets the kernel.  
Also I am not familiar with the source codes and the codes are in such a mass that I failed to find the definition of ```TShape```. Would you please show me where ```TShape``` is defined?

